%S A396250 1,3,11,33,119,337,1043,3153,10679,29377,88643,263713,802907,2383657,
%T A396250 7159163,21490593,71678999,195970657,588043043,1743133633,5293698107,
%U A396250 15690824137,47074569563,141206382913,428857704107,1271093069977,3813312764363,11438262275473
%N A396250 a(n) is the number of ternary sequences of length n with characteristic value 0, as is defined in comments.
%C A396250 A ternary sequence is a sequence in which every term is 0, 1, or 2.
%C A396250 Define the difference sequence of a ternary sequence (x(1), ..., x(n)) as (|x(1) - x(2)|, |x(2) - x(3)|, ..., |x(n-1) - x(n)|). The difference operation is similar to the Ducci game, except that there is no |x(n) - x(1)| term.
%C A396250 For a ternary sequence S of length n, take its difference sequence n-1 times, and the remaining number is the characteristic value of S.
%C A396250 There are exactly 2^(n-1) ternary sequences of length n with characteristic value 2.
%F A396250 a(n) = 3^n * (3^(2^A000120(n-1)) + 1)/(2*3^(2^A000120(n-1))) - 2^(n-1).
%e A396250 Let S = (2, 1, 1, 0). The difference sequence S_1 of S is (1, 0, 1). The difference sequence S_2 of S_1 is (1, 1). The difference sequence of S_2 is (0), so 0 is the characteristic value of S.
%e A396250 For n = 3, (0, 0, 0), (0, 1, 0), (0, 1, 2), (0, 2, 0), (1, 0, 1), (1, 1, 1), (1, 2, 1), (2, 0, 2), (2, 1, 0), (2, 1, 2), and (2, 2, 2) are all ternary sequences of length 3 with characteristic value 0, so a(3) = 11.
%t A396250 a[n_]:=(3^(2^DigitCount[n-1,2,1]) + 1)/2*3^(n - 2^DigitCount[n-1,2,1]) - 2^(n-1); Array[a,28] (* _Stefano Spezia_, Jun 05 2026 *)
%o A396250 (PARI) a(n)=(3^(2^hammingweight(n-1)) + 1)/2*3^(n - 2^hammingweight(n-1)) - 2^(n-1)
%Y A396250 Cf. A000120, A396251, A396614.
